"{\n  \"CO₂ Capture\": {\n    \"err\": \"not found\"\n  },\n  \"Plastic Upcycling\": {\n    \"text\": \"Plastic Upcycling\\nCLOSE\\nSingle-use plastics account for approximately 40% of the plastic produced every year. This global accumulation of plastic pollution has been named a planetary crisis by the United Nations.  Our research teams’ autonomous system taps into the power of bacteria and enzymes to uniquely degrade single-use plastic and convert it into environmentally-benign molecules for reuse and redesign (think: a sneaker, a chair, even a spacesuit). The system has the potential to not only redefine the lifetime of synthetic plastics on Earth, but represent a new frontier for resource utilization in space travel.\\nFounding Scientists\\nMIT MEDIA LAB SPACE EXPLORATION INITIATIVE\\nNATIONAL RENEWABLE ENERGY LABORATORY (NREL)\\nHARVARD MEDICAL SCHOOL\\nWEILL CORNELL MEDICINE\"\n  },\n  \"Honey Bee Resilience\": {\n    \"text\": \"Honey Bee Resilience \\nCLOSE\\nAs pollinators, honey bees are critical to approximately a third of our global food crops. But widespread pesticide use, climate change, disease, and habitat loss have contributed to a population reduction at an alarming rate.  In collaboration with SeedLabs Fellow Dr. Brendan Daisley, we developed the award-winning BioPatty™, which features a proprietary blend of three probiotic strains to increase immune resilience in honey bees. The formulation shows immense potential in tempering the effects of neonicotinoid insecticides, improving survival rates, and restoring honey bee populations around the world.\\nFounding Scientists\\nGREGOR REID, PH.D., MBA\\nBRENDAN A. DAISLEY, PH.D.\\nKey Publications\\nISME\\nNovel probiotic approach to counter Paenibacillus larvae infection in honey bees\\nISME\\nDelivery mechanism can enhance probiotic activity against honey bee pathogens\"\n  }\n}"